			<h3 ><a href="#p1613226">Re: Rebalancing template/spreadsheet</a></h3>
			<p class="author"><a href="./viewtopic.php?p=1613226&amp;sid=2c33e4db6b0d8325257c6ec60ae8857d#p1613226"><img src="./styles/prosilver/imageset/icon_post_target.gif" width="11" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" /></a>by <strong><a href="./memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=10295&amp;sid=2c33e4db6b0d8325257c6ec60ae8857d">DSInvestor</a></strong> &raquo; Wed Feb 13, 2013 3:35 pm </p>

			

			<div class="content">I also like Google Docs which is free.  If you have a gmail account, you have google docs.  The GoogleFinance() function in Google Docs makes it really easy to get prices for  US stocks, ETFs and mutual funds.  Once you have that, you can design the spreadsheet yourself very easily.<br /><br />Here's a page describing the googlefinance() function:<br /><!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://support.google.com/drive/bin/answer.py?hl=en&amp;answer=155178">http://support.google.com/drive/bin/ans ... wer=155178</a><!-- m --></div>

			<div id="sig1613226" class="signature"><a href="http://www.bogleheads.org/wiki/Main_Page" style="text-decoration:none"><img src="http://www.bogleheads.org/w/images/4/4d/BogleheadsWiki.png" /></a></div>

		</div>

		
